[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] The argument to this operation is the key, and the value is returned from the operation.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] , while others return a default value (such as zero, null, or a specific value passed to the constructor).
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] Associative arrays may also include other operations such as determining the number of mappings or constructing an iterator to loop over all the mappings.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] For such operations, the order in which the mappings are returned is usually implementation-defined.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] A multimap generalizes an associative array by allowing multiple values to be associated with a single key.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] A bidirectional map is a related abstract data type in which the mappings operate in both directions: each value must be associated with a unique key, and a second lookup operation takes a value as an argument and looks up the key associated with that value.
