[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] Suppose that the set of loans made by a library is represented in a data structure.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] Each book in a library may be checked out by one patron at a time.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] However, a single patron may be able to check out multiple books.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] Therefore, the information about which books are checked out to which patrons may be represented by an associative array, in which the books are the keys and the patrons are the values.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] A lookup operation on the key "Great Expectations" would return "John".
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] For dictionaries with very few mappings, it may make sense to implement the dictionary using an association list, which is a linked list of mappings.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] With this implementation, the time to perform the basic dictionary operations is linear in the total number of mappings.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] However, it is easy to implement and the constant factors in its running time are small.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] This technique is simple and fast, with each dictionary operation taking constant time.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] However, the space requirement for this structure is the size of the entire keyspace, making it impractical unless the keyspace is small.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] The two major approaches for implementing dictionaries are a hash table or a search tree.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] The most common general-purpose implementation of an associative array is a hash table: an array combined with a hash function that separates each key into a separate "bucket" of the array.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] The basic idea behind a hash table is that accessing an element of an array via its index is a simple, constant-time operation.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] Therefore, the average overhead of an operation for a hash table is only the computation of the key's hash, combined with accessing the corresponding bucket within the array.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] As such, hash tables usually perform in O(1) time, and usually outperform alternative implementations.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] Hash tables must be able to handle collisions: the mapping by the hash function of two different keys to the same bucket of the array.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] The two most widespread approaches to this problem are separate chaining and open addressing.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] In separate chaining, the array does not store the value itself but stores a pointer to another container, usually an association list, that stores all the values matching the hash.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] By contrast, in open addressing, if a hash collision is found, the table seeks an empty spot in an array to store the value in a deterministic manner, usually by looking at the next immediate position in the array.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] Open addressing has a lower cache miss ratio than separate chaining when the table is mostly empty.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] However, as the table becomes filled with more elements, open addressing's performance degrades exponentially.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] Additionally, separate chaining uses less memory in most cases, unless the entries are very small (less than four times the size of a pointer).
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] Another common approach is to implement an associative array with a self-balancing binary search tree, such as an AVL tree or a red–black tree.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] Compared to hash tables, these structures have both strengths and weaknesses.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] The worst-case performance of self-balancing binary search trees is significantly better than that of a hash table, with a time complexity in big O notation of O(log *n*).
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] This is in contrast to hash tables, whose worst-case performance involves all elements sharing a single bucket, resulting in O(*n*) time complexity.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] In addition, and like all binary search trees, self-balancing binary search trees keep their elements in order.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] Thus, traversing its elements follows a least-to-greatest pattern, whereas traversing a hash table can result in elements being in seemingly random order.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] Because they are in order, tree-based maps can also satisfy range queries (find all values between two bounds) whereas a hashmap can only find exact values.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] However, hash tables have a much better average-case time complexity than self-balancing binary search trees of O(1), and their worst-case performance is highly unlikely when a good hash function is used.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] A self-balancing binary search tree can be used to implement the buckets for a hash table that uses separate chaining.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] This allows for average-case constant lookup, but assures a worst-case performance of O(log *n*).
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] Associative arrays may also be stored in unbalanced binary search trees or in data structures specialized to a particular type of keys such as radix trees, tries, Judy arrays, or van Emde Boas trees, though the relative performance of these implementations varies.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] For instance, Judy trees have been found to perform less efficiently than hash tables, while carefully selected hash tables generally perform more efficiently than adaptive radix trees, with potentially greater restrictions on the data types they can handle.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] The advantages of these alternative structures come from their ability to handle additional associative array operations, such as finding the mapping whose key is the closest to a queried key when the query is absent in the set of mappings.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] The basic definition of a dictionary does not mandate an order.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] To guarantee a fixed order of enumeration, ordered versions of the associative array are often used.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] Such ordered dictionaries can be implemented using an association list, by overlaying a doubly linked list on top of a normal dictionary, or by moving the actual data out of the sparse (unordered) array and into a dense insertion-ordered one.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] Associative arrays can be implemented in any programming language as a package and many language systems provide them as part of their standard library.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] In some languages, they are not only built into the standard system, but have special syntax, often using array-like subscripting.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] Built-in syntactic support for associative arrays was introduced in 1969 by SNOBOL4, under the name "table".
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] TMG offered tables with string keys and integer values.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] MUMPS made multi-dimensional associative arrays, optionally persistent, its key data structure.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] SETL supported them as one possible implementation of sets and maps.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] Most modern scripting languages, starting with AWK and including Rexx, Perl, PHP, Tcl, JavaScript, Maple, Python, Ruby, Wolfram Language, Go, and Lua, support associative arrays as a primary container type.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] In many more languages, they are available as library functions without special syntax.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] In PHP and R, all arrays can be associative, except that the keys are limited to integers and strings.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] In JavaScript (see also JSON), all objects behave as associative arrays with string-valued keys, while the Map and WeakMap types take arbitrary objects as keys.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] In Lua, they are used as the primitive building block for all data structures.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] In Visual FoxPro, they are called *Collections*.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] The D language also supports associative arrays.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] Many programs using associative arrays will need to store that data in a more permanent form, such as a computer file.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] A common solution to this problem is a generalized concept known as *archiving* or *serialization*, which produces a text or binary representation of the original objects that can be written directly to a file.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] This is most commonly implemented in the underlying object model, like .Net or Cocoa, which includes standard functions that convert the internal data into text.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] The program can create a complete text representation of any group of objects by calling these methods, which are almost always already implemented in the base associative array class.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] For programs that use very large data sets, this sort of individual file storage is not appropriate, and a database management system (DB) is required.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] Some DB systems natively store associative arrays by serializing the data and then storing that serialized data and the key.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] Individual arrays can then be loaded or saved from the database using the key to refer to them.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] These key–value stores have been used for many years and have a history as long as that of the more common relational database (RDBs), but a lack of standardization, among other reasons, limited their use to certain niche roles.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] RDBs were used for these roles in most cases, although saving objects to a RDB can be complicated, a problem known as object-relational impedance mismatch.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] After approximately 2010, the need for high-performance databases suitable for cloud computing and more closely matching the internal structure of the programs using them led to a renaissance in the key–value store market.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/augmented-map] These systems can store and retrieve associative arrays in a native fashion, which can greatly improve performance in common web-related workflows.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] In computer science, a **binary search tree** (**BST**), also called an **ordered** or **sorted binary tree**, is a rooted binary tree data structure with the key of each internal node being greater than all the keys in the respective node's left subtree and less than the ones in its right subtree.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] The time complexity of operations on the binary search tree is linear with respect to the height of the tree.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees allow binary search for fast lookup, addition, and removal of data items.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] Since the nodes in a BST are laid out so that each comparison skips about half of the remaining tree, the lookup performance is proportional to that of binary logarithm.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] BSTs were devised in the 1960s for the problem of efficient storage of labeled data and are attributed to Conway Berners-Lee and David Wheeler.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] The performance of a binary search tree is dependent on the order of insertion of the nodes into the tree since arbitrary insertions may lead to degeneracy; several variations of the binary search tree can be built with guaranteed worst-case performance.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] The basic operations include: search, traversal, insert and delete.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] BSTs with guaranteed worst-case complexities perform better than an unsorted array, which would require linear search time.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] The complexity analysis of BST shows that, on average, the insert, delete and search takes $\Theta (\log n)$ for n nodes.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] In the worst case, they degrade to that of a singly linked list: $O(n)$ .
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] To address the boundless increase of the tree height with arbitrary insertions and deletions, self-balancing variants of BSTs are introduced to bound the worst lookup complexity to that of the binary logarithm.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] AVL trees were the first self-balancing binary search trees, invented in 1962 by Georgy Adelson-Velsky and Evgenii Landis.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees can be used to implement abstract data types such as dynamic sets, lookup tables and priority queues, and used in sorting algorithms such as tree sort.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] The binary search tree algorithm was discovered independently by several researchers, including P.F.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] Windley, Andrew Donald Booth, Andrew Colin, Thomas N.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] The algorithm is attributed to Conway Berners-Lee and David Wheeler, who used it for storing labeled data in magnetic tapes in 1960.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] One of the earliest and popular binary search tree algorithm is that of Hibbard.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] The time complexity of a binary search tree increases boundlessly with the tree height if the nodes are inserted in an arbitrary order, therefore self-balancing binary search trees were introduced to bound the height of the tree to $O(\log n)$ .
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] Various **height-balanced** binary search trees were introduced to confine the tree height, such as AVL trees, Treaps, and red–black trees.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are also efficacious in sortings and search algorithms.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are also a fundamental data structure used in construction of abstract data structures such as sets, multisets, and associative arrays.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] Searching in a binary search tree for a specific key can be programmed recursively or iteratively.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] Searching begins by examining the root node.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] If the tree is nil, the key being searched for does not exist in the tree.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] Otherwise, if the key equals that of the root, the search is successful and the node is returned.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] If the key is less than that of the root, the search proceeds by examining the left subtree.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] Similarly, if the key is greater than that of the root, the search proceeds by examining the right subtree.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] This process is repeated until the key is found or the remaining subtree is ${\text{nil}}$ .
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] If the searched key is not found after a ${\text{nil}}$ subtree is reached, then the key is not present in the tree.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] The following pseudocode implements the BST search procedure through recursion.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] The recursive procedure continues until a ${\text{nil}}$ or the ${\text{key}}$ being searched for are encountered.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] The recursive version of the search can be "unrolled" into a while loop.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] On most machines, the iterative version is found to be more efficient.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] Since the search may proceed till some leaf node, the running time complexity of BST search is $O(h)$ where h is the height of the tree.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] However, the worst case for BST search is $O(n)$ where n is the total number of nodes in the BST, because an unbalanced BST may degenerate to a linked list.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] However, if the BST is height-balanced the height is $O(\log n)$ .
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] For certain operations, given a node ${\text{x}}$ , finding the successor or predecessor of ${\text{x}}$ is crucial.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] Assuming all the keys of a BST are distinct, the successor of a node ${\text{x}}$ in a BST is the node with the smallest key greater than ${\text{x}}$ 's key.
[src:weight-balanced-tree/binary-search-tree] On the other hand, the predecessor of a node ${\text{x}}$ in a BST is the node with the largest key smaller than ${\text{x}}$ 's key.
